    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_04_18_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <note>66</note>
                        <date when="1812-04-18">April 18<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1812</date></dateline> </opener>
                    
                <p> 
                    
                    My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir,</persName> Though we have not written to you<lb/>
                    for some months, and though we have not even<lb/>
                    expressed our gratitude, or our high value for<lb/>
                    the Work you did us the honor and the <choice><orig>kind-<lb/>
                    -ness</orig><reg>kindness</reg></choice> to send us yet we feel security that <hi rend="underline">you</hi><lb/>
                    have not suspected us of having utterly changed<lb/>
                    our natures - and we must have utterly<lb/>
                    changed them before we could become <choice><orig>ne-<lb/>
                    glectful</orig><reg>neglectful</reg></choice> of you or insensible to the superior<lb/>
                    value of your Writings and the <choice><orig>unpurchase-<lb/>
                    able</orig><reg>unpurchasable</reg></choice> happiness of your friendship - For<lb/>
                    several weeks I was hard at work at a <title ref="./Workography.xml#Essay2">Report<lb/>
                    on Roads &amp; Wheel carriages</title> for the Committee<lb/>
                    of the House of Commons &amp; till this was<lb/>
                    finished I could not indulge myself in<lb/>
                    any higher work of literature or science.<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    - Now when that drudgery is over we have been<lb/>
                    enjoying your <title ref="./Workography.xml#Ratio1" cert="medium">book</title> - My dear Sir you<lb/>
                    have <del>pressed</del> condensed more knowledge<lb/>
                    and wisdom into a small compass than<lb/>
                    ever <add>before</add> was squeezed into the same space<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    - A dozen hams converted into essence of<lb/>
                    ham &amp; contained in a tiny phial! -<lb/></p>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_04_18_page02.jpg"/>
                    
                    <p> - Your work is inestimable for the few who can<lb/>
                    judge of it; but it will be lost upon the many<lb/>
                    who cannot submit to the labor of unremitting
                    attention to a series of logical propositions <add>&amp; demonstrations</add><lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    - You have made a <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EuclX1">Euclid</persName> for legislators<lb/>
                    Happy would it be for the world if they would<lb/>
                    have patience &amp; sense enough to study it -<lb/>
                    - And that it has <hi rend="underline">already</hi> spread among<lb/>
                    the first politicians and the men of the<lb/>
                    highest abilities in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> we have had<lb/>
                    the pleasure of perceiving in the <add>late</add> speeches<lb/>
                    of some of the most celebrated men on<lb/>
                    both sides in both houses of parliament -<lb/>
                    We have frequently marked them stealing<lb/>
                    from you when they did not quote you,<lb/>
                    making themselves fine with a bit of your<lb/>
                    sterling gold beaten out &amp; fillagreed into<lb/>
                    ornaments which have attrated universal<lb/>
                    admiration - Others more honest and<lb/>
                    of course more wise have openly referred<lb/>
                    to the authority of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">Bentham</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Dumont</persName> and<lb/>
                    have proved that they have imbibed <add>some of</add> the <hi rend="underline"><choice><orig>spi-<lb/>
                    rit</orig><reg>spirit</reg></choice> of the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Ratio1" cert="medium">book</title></hi> - The ideas on Reward and<lb/>
                    punishment - the whole that has been said<lb/>
                    in Parliament on <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Botany-Bay_NSW_AU">Botany Bay</placeName> - prisons - penal<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_04_18_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>67</note>
                    statutes is all taken from your work, and you have<lb/>
                    reason to rejoice that these notions are now <choice><orig>be-<lb/>
                    coming</orig><reg>becoming</reg></choice> familiar &amp; that they are passing down<lb/>
                    from philosophers to the mass of the people - The<lb/>
                    more these subjects are discussed, the higher your<lb/>
                    fame must rise - But why my dear Sir, Oh why<lb/>
                    will you not publish an original work in your<lb/>
                    own name? - Your letters to us display talents<lb/>
                    of such superior and various kinds as ought<lb/>
                    to be brought before the public in a work of your<lb/>
                    own - a work in which you should not <choice><orig>con-<lb/>
                    demn</orig><reg>condemn</reg></choice> your mind to the torture of fitting it<lb/>
                    perpetually to <add>another man's thoughts &amp; cramping your fancy to</add> the <del>standar</del> divisions and <choice><orig>sub-<lb/>
                    divisions</orig><reg>subdivisions</reg></choice> of an abstruse subject<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    We have much to say to you about your work<lb/>
                    and much more about <hi rend="underline">your</hi> future fam<damage><gap/></damage><lb/>
                    ,-more than we could put in the compass of<lb/>
                    a letter &amp; we have delayed writing in hopes<lb/>
                    of speaking to you - We had intended to be<lb/>
                    in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> next month, but circumstances<lb/>
                    have again occurred that oblige us to delay<lb/>
                    our journey till next spring-<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Cannot you <hi rend="underline">now</hi> come to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> and<lb/>
                    spend your summer with us? - In the<lb/>
                    hope that you <hi rend="underline">can</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">will</hi>, we reserve all that<lb/>
                    we have to say till we meet -<lb/></p>
                    <closer>
                    With the highest esteem and regard <del>I am</del> <add>we are</add><lb/>
                    my dear friend your obliged &amp; attached<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Ric<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> L</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/></closer>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_04_18_page04.jpg"/>
                    <closer><address>
                         
                    <addrLine><placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Collon_IE">Collon</placeName> <date>April Eighteen 1812</date></addrLine>
                    <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">S. Dumont Esq<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName></addrLine>
                    <addrLine><placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Haymarket-36_ENK">36 Haymarket</placeName></addrLine>
                    <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#FostJ1" cert="low">J Foster</persName><placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName></addrLine></address>
                    </closer>
                    
                  
                
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
</TEI>



